 United Kingdom":"Giggleswick, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Giggleswick, Yorkshire, England":"Giggleswick, Yorkshire, England","Stainforth, Yorkshire,England":"Stainforth, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1334–":"about 1334–Deceased","1334–1393":"1334–1393","1362–1390":"1362–1390","1365–1430":"1365–1430","–1437":"–1437","1334–Female":"1334–Deceased","1362":"1362","Abt 1334":"about 1334","1382":"1382","1393":"1393","1390":"1390","1437":"1437","1337":"1337","1334":"1334","Abt 1365":"about 1365","1453":"1453","1365":"1365","1430":"1430","about 1362":"about 1362","Giggleswick, Craven district, North Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Giggleswick, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Giggleswick, Yorkshire, England":"Giggleswick, Yorkshire, England","Stainforth, Yorkshire,England":"Stainforth, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Stainforth","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name; one group of family names is from Stainforth in Hatfield (near Doncaster, WR Yorks), and another from Stainforth in Giggleswick (near Settle, WR Yorks). The first of these has probably become confused with   Staniforth   (from a locality in Sheffield)."],"variants":[{"name":"Stanforth","meanings":["English:","mainly a variant of   Stanford  , which may have migrated to North Yorkshire and Northumberland from Norfolk and Suffolk by the North Sea coastal trade.","variant of   Staniforth  ."]},{"name":"Staniforth","meanings":["English: habitational name from an unidentified place, probably near Sheffield (Yorkshire), where the surname is common. The placename appears to derive from Old English <i>stānig</i> ‘stony’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’."]},{"name":"Stainford","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, in origin a local name from the very numerous places named with the Old English elements <i>stān</i> ‘stone’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’. Use as a given name may have been influenced by the prestigious Californian university named after  Senator Leland Stanford , on whose land it was built. It may also in some cases have been adopted as an alternative elaboration of   Stan ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":3,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":48,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLev